  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal statutes:\n- The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- The USA PATRIOT Act\n- The Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Key provisions:\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Criminalize financial transactions involving proceeds from illegal activities\n- Establish reporting requirements for cash transactions over $10,000\n- Impose penalties for non-compliance\n\n3. Specific federal criminal statutes:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (laundering of monetary instruments)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from unlawful activities)\n\n4. State-level statutes:\n- Many states have their own money laundering laws that complement federal statutes\n- Provide additional mechanisms for prosecution and asset forfeiture\n\n5. International cooperation:\n- The U.S. works with international organizations like FATF (Financial Action Task Force)\n- Participates in global efforts to combat money laundering\n\nThese statutes create a comprehensive legal framework for preventing, detecting, and prosecuting money laundering activities.",
